=== IAM Roles for EC2 - Test Commands and Output ===

--- Step 6: Confirm No Credentials Exist on Instance ---
Command: ls -la ~/.aws/ 2>/dev/null || echo "No ~/.aws directory."
Result: No ~/.aws directory.

--- Step 7: Test the Role - Identity Check ---
Command: aws sts get-caller-identity
Result:
{
    "UserId": "AROA...:i-xxxxxxxxx",
    "Account": "743631836010",
    "Arn": "arn:aws:sts::743631836010:assumed-role/ec2-s3-cloudwatch-role/i-xxxxxxxxx"
}
Confirms: authenticated as assumed-role, not an IAM user, with no
aws configure ever run on this instance.

--- Step 9: Capture Trust Policy (run from laptop, not instance) ---
Command: aws iam get-role --role-name ec2-s3-cloudwatch-role \
  --query 'Role.AssumeRolePolicyDocument'
Result:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": { "Service": "ec2.amazonaws.com" },
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
  }]
}

--- Step 10: Locate Source of Credentials (IMDSv2) ---
Command:
TOKEN=$(curl -sX PUT "http://169.254.169.254/latest/api/token" \
  -H "X-aws-ec2-metadata-token-ttl-seconds: 300")
curl -sH "X-aws-ec2-metadata-token: $TOKEN" \
  http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/ec2-s3-cloudwatch-role

Result: Response included Code: "Success", AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey,
Token, and an Expiration timestamp approximately 6 hours in the future -
confirming genuinely short-lived, auto-rotating credentials.
(Actual credential values omitted from this file per the lab's security
guidance - these expire automatically regardless.)
